# Architecture Rules

These rules have the highest priority and must always be followed.

If another rule conflicts with this file, this file wins.

---

# Project Architecture

Architecture Style:

- Clean Architecture
- Modular Monolith
- Vertical Slice Architecture
- CQRS

References:

- docs/tech-architecture.md
- docs/folder-structure.md
- docs/coding-standards.md

---

# Mandatory Dependency Direction

Dependencies must always point inward.

Allowed:

Api
→ Application
→ Domain

Infrastructure
→ Application
→ Domain

Persistence
→ Domain

Shared
→ No business dependencies

Contracts
→ Shared

---

Forbidden:

Domain
→ Infrastructure

Domain
→ Persistence

Domain
→ Api

Application
→ Api

Persistence
→ Api

Infrastructure
→ Api

---

# Layer Responsibilities

## Api Layer

Responsibilities:

- Controllers
- Middleware
- Authentication
- Dependency Injection
- Swagger

Must NOT contain:

- Business Logic
- Database Queries
- External API Calls

Controllers must remain thin.

---

## Application Layer

Responsibilities:

- Commands
- Queries
- Handlers
- Validators
- DTOs
- Use Cases

All business logic belongs here.

---

## Domain Layer

Responsibilities:

- Entities
- Enums
- Value Objects
- Domain Rules
- Domain Exceptions

Must remain framework independent.

Must NOT contain:

- EF Core
- HTTP Clients
- Logging
- Infrastructure Services

---

## Persistence Layer

Responsibilities:

- DbContext
- Entity Configurations
- Migrations
- Repositories

Must NOT contain:

- Business Logic
- HTTP Calls

---

## Infrastructure Layer

Responsibilities:

- External APIs
- OAuth Providers
- Third Party Integrations
- Email Services
- Storage Providers

Must NOT contain:

- Domain Logic

---

# Vertical Slice Rules

Every feature must be organized by feature.

Preferred:

Features/

├── Auth
├── Dashboard
├── AffiliateLinks
├── Orders
├── Withdrawals
├── Admin
└── Webhooks

---

Each use case should have its own folder.

Example:

AffiliateLinks/

└── GenerateAffiliateLink/

```
├── GenerateAffiliateLinkCommand.cs
├── GenerateAffiliateLinkHandler.cs
├── GenerateAffiliateLinkValidator.cs
├── GenerateAffiliateLinkRequest.cs
└── GenerateAffiliateLinkResponse.cs
```

---

One Use Case = One Folder

Do not group unrelated handlers together.

---

# CQRS Rules

Commands:

Modify data.

Examples:

- CreateWithdrawalRequest
- GenerateAffiliateLink
- ApproveWithdrawal

Queries:

Read data only.

Examples:

- GetDashboard
- GetOrders
- GetUserProfile

Queries must never modify state.

Commands must not return entities.

---

# Entity Rules

Entities represent business concepts.

Examples:

- User
- Order
- AffiliateLink
- WithdrawRequest
- CommissionTransaction

Entities should protect their state.

Prefer:

public decimal AvailableBalance
{
get;
private set;
}

Avoid public setters unless necessary.

---

# DTO Rules

Never expose entities directly.

Always create DTOs.

Allowed:

UserDto

OrderDto

DashboardDto

Forbidden:

return User

return Order

---

# Validation Rules

Use FluentValidation.

Validation belongs in Application Layer.

Never place validation inside Controllers.

---

# Repository Rules

Repositories are for persistence only.

Repositories must NOT contain:

- Business Logic
- External API Calls
- Authentication Logic

---

# External Integration Rules

All external integrations must go through Infrastructure Layer.

Examples:

- Accesstrade API
- Google OAuth
- Email Providers

Never call external APIs directly from:

- Controllers
- Handlers
- Domain Entities

Use abstractions/interfaces.

---

# Folder Structure Rules

Always follow:

docs/folder-structure.md

Do not create arbitrary folders.

Forbidden examples:

Services/
Helpers/
Utils/
Managers/

at root project level.

Everything must belong to a defined layer.

---

# Database Rules

Database schema must follow:

docs/database-design.md

Enums must follow:

docs/enums.md

Do not invent new enum values without updating enums.md.

---

# API Rules

All APIs must follow:

docs/api-specification.md

Use standard response wrapper.

Do not create inconsistent response formats.

---

# Documentation Rules

When introducing:

- New feature
- New module
- New entity
- New API

Check whether documentation must be updated.

Relevant docs include:

- product-requirements.md
- database-design.md
- user-flows.md
- api-specification.md

---

# Testing Rules

Critical business logic should be testable.

Avoid tightly coupling logic to framework code.

Business logic should remain unit-test friendly.

---

# AI Assistant Instructions

Before generating code:

1. Identify target layer.
2. Verify dependency direction.
3. Verify folder location.
4. Check existing patterns.
5. Reuse existing abstractions.

Always prefer consistency over creativity.

Do not introduce new architectural patterns unless explicitly requested.

---

# Definition Of Success

Generated code is considered correct only if:

✓ Respects Clean Architecture

✓ Respects Vertical Slice Architecture

✓ Respects CQRS

✓ Respects folder structure

✓ Respects dependency direction

✓ Keeps controllers thin

✓ Keeps business logic in Application Layer

✓ Keeps Domain framework independent

Architecture consistency is more important than implementation speed.
